content.description: Move left from the start using pretty terrible, sloping holds but huge feet. A right-facing sidepull along the way offers up something different to grab. Finish with a big move up and left to a better hold above the low boulder then back right to the top.
content.location: Start on the right hand side (blunt arete) of the boulder below an overhang on some square cut sidepull holds, this is as viewed from the benches.

content.description: Start on opposing sidepulls, and work straight up an over the bulge using a pinch, crimps, a sidepull, and a heel hook to reach a good, incut crimp at the top.
content.location: Start under a small bulge on the southwest side of the block.

content.description: From the blocky jugs, move right to a cool edge/pinch, then go up on some edges to the base of the right-trending flake. Follow the flake to the top. The crux is the first few moves. Once you gain the flake, it is over.
content.location: On the road side of the boulder. Start from a SDS on the left side of the face at some blocky cracked jugs and angle up and right aiming for the juggy flake.

content.description: Climb the crack on the Eastern face.
content.location:
Boulder D is the right boulder in the group of three boulders from the road. It is called Prominent Block in the

Colorado Bouldering

book.

content.description: Climb the arete on the Southeast side of the boulder.
content.location:
Boulder D is the right boulder in the group of three boulders from the road. It is called Prominent Block in the

Colorado Bouldering

book.

content.description: Sit start on incut crimps, grab a right hand sidepull, and keep working straight up to better holds.
content.location:
It climbs the middle of the west face on small but incut crimps with good footholds about 5 feet left of the

V3 Bulge

.
